05667nam a22007695i 9789048543953DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20192019ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485439537 a10.1515/97890485439532doi  a(DE-B1597)544477  a(OCoLC)1130062352  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1993.5.A1bS34 2019 7aCOM0700002bisacsh04a302.2322300aScreen Genealogies :bFrom Optical Device to Environmental Medium /ced. by Francesco Casetti, Craig Buckley, Rüdiger Campe. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMediaMatters00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tBecoming Screen -- t1. Primal Screens -- t2. 'Schutz und Schirm': Screening in German During Early Modern Times -- tSpaces -- t3. Face and Screen: Toward a Genealogy of the Media Façade -- t4. Sensing Screens: From Surface to Situation -- t5. 'Taking the Plunge': The New Immersive Screens -- tAtmospheres -- t6. The Atmospheric Screen: Turner, Hazlitt, Ruskin -- t7. The Fog Medium: Visualizing and Engineering the Atmosphere -- t8. The Charge of a Light Barricade: Optics and Ballistics in the Ambiguous Being of Screens -- tFormats -- t9. Flat Bayreuth: A Genealogy of Opera as Screened -- t10. Imaginary Screens: The Hypnotic Gesture and Early Film -- t11. Material. Human. Divine. Notes on the Vertical Screen -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aAgainst the grain of the growing literature on screens, *Screen Genealogies* argues that the present excess of screens cannot be understood as an expansion and multiplication of the movie screen nor of the video display. Rather, screens continually exceed the optical histories in which they are most commonly inscribed. As contemporary screens become increasingly decomposed into a distributed field of technologically interconnected surfaces and interfaces, we more readily recognize the deeper spatial and environmental interventions that have long been a property of screens. For most of its history, a screen was a filter, a divide, a shelter, or a camouflage. A genealogy stressing transformation and descent rather than origins and roots emphasizes a deeper set of intersecting and competing definitions of the screen, enabling new thinking about what the screen might yet become.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspects. 0aMass media. 4aDigital and Social Media. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 7aCOMPUTERS / User Interfaces.2bisacsh  aScreens, Media Archeology, Environmental Media, Visual Studies,.1 aBuckley, Craig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuckley, Craig, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampe, Rüdiger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampe, Rüdiger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCasetti, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasetti, Francesco, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aElcott, Noam M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEugeni, Ruggero, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuruhata, Yuriko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreuzer, Gundula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeters, John Durham, econtributor.4ctb4https://